\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize, the questions that seem to arise are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For which points 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \delta\eta\right\Vert _{p}<\infty$
\end_inset

? What is the nature of this set? Is it countable? Does it have a measure?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For which points 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{p}<\infty$
\end_inset

? We've concluded above that this should hold when the winding number is
 locally unchanged; for example, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is in one of the Arnold tongues.
 What is the structure of these regions? What is the correct way to talk
 about this structure?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For which points 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{p}$
\end_inset

 a smooth (approximately linear) function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\eta$
\end_inset

? We've concluded above that this should hold when 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a periodic orbit that is not on the cusp chaos, Can this
 be demonstrated more carefully and clearly?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These questions should now make the inspiration of the Moore plane a bit
 more obvious: any point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{p}=\infty$
\end_inset

 is metrically disconnected from it's neighbors.
 One can use this to infer a topology, with that topology being discrete,
 at such points.
 But this is not all; other nearby questions easily suggest themselves.
\end_layout

