\begin_layout Subsection
Bin-counting and measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A deeper and more sophisticated perspective is provided through the method
 of bin-counting or histogramming.
 This enables a simple numerical technique for determining the period of
 an orbit, independently of using the Poincare recurrence time to obtain
 it.
 It also leads directly to the concept of invarient measures, a central
 concept from ergodic theory.
 Invariant measures consisting only of discrete points correspond to periodic
 orbits; invariant measure that have continuous regions correspond to chaotic
 orbits.
 The correspondence is sketched below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerical approach provides a good place to launch from.
 Divide the unit interval into 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 bins.
 Several hundred to several thousand bins are enough to show something interesti
ng.
 For each iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}$
\end_inset

, compute the bin number 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\left\lfloor My_{n}\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 and increment the bincount on that bin.
 Orbits of period 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 will typically populate 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 bins.
 Near period bifurcations (saddle points), the Lyapunov exponent will be
 vanishing, and orbits will always engage in a slow walk, slowly converging
 to the limit cycle.
 Thus, for periodic orbits near period bifurcations, there will be some
 slop, as counts spill over into bins neighboring the limit cycle.
 This can be mitigated by pre-iterating: counting does not start until some
 minimum number of iterations have been done.
 This allows the periodic orbits to settle down and converge to their limit
 cycles.
 Counting the number of non-empty bins (rejecting the low-count bins as
 noise) provides a direct measure of the period.
 For a periodic orbit, each non-empty bin should be visited the same number
 of times; any spill-over or deficit should be ascribed to iteration near
 saddle points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chaotic orbits do not visit a finite set of distinct points, but instead
 are ergodic over a measureable set.
 The idea of the invariant measure is described more closely below; from
 the bin-counting point of view, it means that a large fraction of the bins,
 or possibly all of them are visited during iteration.
 This holds true, even if the bins are made infinitessimally tiny.
 The support of the measure is the fraction of the unit interval on which
 the measure is non-vanishing; in bin-counting terms, it is the fraction
