\begin_layout Standard
The measure is termed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

invariant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, because it corresponds to the Frobenius-Perron eigenvalue of one, for
 the corresponding transfer operator.
 Wandering a bit off-topic, lets sketch this for completeness.
 For any given iterated function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[0,1\right]\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, define the transfer operator (alternately called the FrobeniusPeron operator)
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}g\right]\left(y\right)=\sum_{x\in f^{-1}\left(y\right)}\frac{1}{\left|f^{\prime}\left(x\right)\right|}g\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

This busy expression can be understood as follows.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

suitable space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of functions on the unit interval, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 More on what is meant by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

suitable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, below.
 In the meantime, one may take 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 denotes the derivative; the reciprocal can be recognized as the Jacobian.
 The FrobeniusPeron operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is an operator, in that it maps functions to functions.
 As a operator, it has a spectrum: in general a spectrum with discrete parts,
 as well as continuous parts; all of the usual considerations about the
 spectra of operators apply, in general.
 For suitably tame function spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, the largest eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 will be one, corresponding to a unique eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{f}\mu=\mu
\]

\end_inset

This eigenfunction can be identified as the invariant measure of the iterated
 map.
 It is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

invariant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 doesn't change it.
 It is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, because the probability that the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th iterate of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, write 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}=f\circ f\circ\cdots\circ f$
\end_inset

 as the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 composed 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 times with itself.
 Then, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $a<f^{n}\left(x\right)<b$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}\mu\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The precise form of the FrobeniusPeron operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 and the structure of its spectrum depends strongly on the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Working with spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 defined to have a polynomial basis and forcing uniform convergence usually
 results in an operator with a discrete spectrum.
 Since all but the first eigenvalue are less than one, the eigenfunctions
 are termed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

decaying
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 They correspond to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wandering set
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of dynamical systems that are not conservative.
 That is, one may start iteration with some initial 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 and find that in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}\left(x_{0}\right)\notin\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 almost certainly.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wandered away
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}\mu\left(x\right)dx=0$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conservative system
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 results when one works with the subset of the unit interval where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is non-vanishing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The situation is not always so simple.
 Working with Hilbert spaces or Banach spaces for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 can result in continuous, rather than discrete spectra.
 Note that functions belonging to the Banach space 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

