\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to imagine that one way to explore neighboring values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 is to take the point-wise Laplacian of the orbits.
 This proves to be a not very good idea, as will be revealed shortly.
 Nontheless, its just interesting enough to deserve a mention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 5-point discrete Laplacian, at each iteration, can be defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)=4x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)-x_{n}\left(\omega-\delta\omega,K\right)-x_{n}\left(\omega+\delta\omega,K\right)-x_{n}\left(\omega,K-\delta K\right)-x_{n}\left(\omega,K+\delta K\right)
\]

\end_inset

for some suitably small 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\omega,\delta K\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 One then considers the average Laplacian, over many iterations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{N}\left(\omega,K\right)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}\nabla^{2}x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)
\]

\end_inset

Several figures below, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Laplapce-abs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Log-of-Laplacian"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 show the result.
 This sounds like a good idea, until one realizes that 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{N}\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 changes sign, when one crosses a boundary.
 Intuitively, one might say that taking a derivative to the left is minus
 that of taking a derivative to the right.
 The same for the discrete Laplacian.
 As a kind of second derivative, one could think of it as being immune to
 such awkward behavior.
 This is not so, when it straddles a boundary.
 This can be belabored in greater detail, if one wishes.
 If not, then skip the next few sentences.
 They don't say anything important.
 So, for example, assume that one can find a region where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)\approx x_{n}\left(\omega-\delta\omega,K\right)\approx x_{n}\left(\omega+\delta\omega,K\right)\approx x_{n}\left(\omega,K-\delta K\right)$
\end_inset

 but that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)\ne x_{n}\left(\omega,K+\delta K\right)$
\end_inset

 in a strong way.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)\approx x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)-x_{n}\left(\omega,K+\delta K\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Consider shifting over to the next pixel, located at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega,K+\delta K\right)$
\end_inset

.
 At this pixel, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}x_{n}\left(\omega,K+\delta K\right)\approx-\nabla^{2}x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 and so likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $L\left(\omega,K+\delta K\right)\approx-L\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In more abstract terms, the first derivative of the Heaviside step function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Dirac delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The second derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{\prime}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 which is a pair of spikes, one going positive, one going negative, with
 the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{\prime}\left(x\right)=-\delta^{\prime}\left(-x\right)$
\end_inset

: the sign flips.
 Dang.
 This kind of nasty behavior near edges makes the Laplacian less than ideal
 as an experimental tool.
\end_layout

