\begin_layout Standard
Quite peculiar is the diamond in the center of the figure.
 It is quite unlike any other region of the map (except, of course, those
 regions where it reappears streched and squashed.) The most remarkable property
 is how undifferentiated it is: there is no visible small-scale structure.
 In this sense, perhaps, one should say tat the orbits in this region truly
 are uncorrelated and random.
 This is fundamentally different from the other colored regions, which suggest
 the presence of structure.
 Comparing to the winding number chart, it is seen again that the winding
 number behaves quite tamely in this diamond.
 As the lower part of the diamond is quite red, one concludes that the there
 are large excursions there, as well.
 However, comparing to the recurrence chart 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Poincare-recurrence-time"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the orbits in the diamond can be seen to have very low recurrence times.
 They would seem to be periodic with very short periods.
 This would seem to point at a contradiction or a paradox: from the winding
 number chart, one concludes, as before, that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\approx n\Omega$
\end_inset

 in this region.
 From the recurrance chart, the periods appear to be all short, and so there
 is not enough time for a large excursion to occur.
 Perhaps te resolution to this paradox is that the recurrence time is being
 measured in a misleading way? Or rather, that the recurrence time cannot
 be taken as an accurate proxy for the period?
\end_layout

